0.6.0 release record — how these changes were validated.

Method: two layers. Layer A drove a nested Claude Code (Sonnet) in tmux with
the plugin loaded via --plugin-dir, tracing every tool call via
--output-format stream-json. Layer B exercised the cos driver directly with
29 assertions against a live control plane, including negative cases.

Results: 24/29 on the first Layer B pass; every remaining failure was
investigated and either fixed or explained. Layer A confirmed the plugin
loads, the SessionStart hook fires, the skill self-triggers without a slash
command, and the prototype -> public URL -> verify flow works end to end
(HTTP 200, correct body).

Three commands were found to be entirely broken in 0.5.0:
  - fork crashed on every run (multibyte parsed into the variable name),
    leaving the box paused and the clone orphaned. The orphan was identified
    by confirming it carried the parent's marker file.
  - sync never passed the sandbox positional, so it always failed into a log
    while cos status reported a healthy pid.
  - sync of any /tmp path was rejected by the CLI because cos resolved it to
    /private/tmp on macOS.
All three are fixed and verified live (sync propagates in ~10s).

Documentation claims were checked rather than trusted. Corrected: spawn
timing, egress enforcement semantics, cluster DNS (FQDN only — the bare short
name is NXDOMAIN, proven by splitting the DNS/IP/TCP hops on a live two-box
cluster), shape "plan gating", and quota figures.

Known and unresolved, tracked for follow-up:
  - The skill is never invoked during autonomous use; the model reaches for
    Bash directly, so SKILL.md is not in context when the verb is chosen. The
    critical rule was moved into the SessionStart hook as mitigation, which
    stopped the project-box misuse but not the habit of hand-staging files
    with tar/base64 instead of using offload. This is a skill-triggering
    problem and wants the description-optimization loop.
  - Deferred from the adversarial review: sync/tunnel pids are killed without
    verifying process identity (PID reuse), and a second sync overwrites the
    recorded pid without stopping the first. Both pre-existing.

Reviewed by Codex (adversarial pass): 0 critical, 3 high, 6 medium, 1 low.
All findings introduced by this release were fixed before landing.
